07343nam a22007575i 9781477327449DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773274497 a10.7560/3274252doi  a(DE-B1597)653201  a(OCoLC)1394872766  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGV875.H64bA78 2023 7aSPO0000002bisacsh04a796.35764097641411223/eng/2023042800aAstros and Asterisks :bHouston's Sign-Stealing Scandal Explained /ced. by Jonathan Silverman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTerry and Jan Todd Series on Physical Culture and Sports00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Houston Astros Timeline -- tPART I HISTORIES OF CHEATING IN BASEBALL -- tCHAPTER 1 Baseball, Hot Dogs, Apple Pie, and Cheating: Blame It on the Pitchers -- tCHAPTER 2 Cheating versus Gamesmanship: Ethical Relativism in Baseball? -- tCHAPTER 3 “This Is Not a Cultural Issue”: The Astros’ (and Baseball’s) Willingness to Overlook Domestic Violence -- tCHAPTER 4 Round Up the Usual Suspects: Cheating in Baseball -- tPART II THE SCANDAL UNFOLDS -- tCHAPTER 5 Finally, a Fun Baseball Scandal -- tCHAPTER 6 What Is the Sound of One Bat Slapping? Reading the Houston Astros’ Trash Can -- tCHAPTER 7 Blame Is a Tangled Mess in Astros Sign- Stealing Scandal -- tPART III FANS AND THE SCANDAL -- tCHAPTER 8 Interview with a Bang Counter: A Q&A with Tony Adams -- tCHAPTER 9 Reckoning with Tainted Love: What the Astros Scandal Reveals of Sports Fandom -- tCHAPTER 10 “To Learn Baseball”: A Transatlantic Dialogue on the Astros and the American Ways of Winning -- tPART IV THE SCANDAL AND ITS ETHICAL DILEMMAS -- tCHAPTER 11 Baseball Has No Love for Truth Tellers -- tCHAPTER 12 Bad Apples or Bad Astros? Collective Responsibility and the Perils of Team Loyalty -- tCHAPTER 13 From Protector to Whistleblower: Being a “Good” Teammate When Cheating Occurs -- tPART V TECHNOLOGY AND THE SCANDAL -- tCHAPTER 14 Stealing Signs: Technology, Surveillance, and Policing inside and outside the Game -- tCHAPTER 15 The Spreadsheet in the Garden: Analytics and the Sign- Stealing Scandal -- tAPPENDIX “Defendant Houston Astros”: Michael Bolsinger vs. The Houston Astros -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn in-depth and multiperspectival look at the Astros’ sign-stealing scandal and its roots in the culture of baseball fandom. In 2017 the Houston Astros won their first World Series title, a particularly uplifting victory for the city following Hurricane Harvey. But two years later, the feel-good energy was gone after The Athletic revealed that the Astros had stolen signs from opposing catchers during their championship season, perhaps even during the playoffs and World Series. Their methods were at once high-tech and crude: staff took video of opponents’ pitching signals and transmitted the footage in real time to the Astros’ dugout, where players banged on trash cans to signal to their teammates at bat which pitches were coming their way. Wry observers labeled them the Asterisks, pointing to the title that no longer seemed so earned. Astros and Asterisks examines the scandal from historical, journalistic, legal, ethical, and cultural perspectives. Authors delve into the Astros’ winning-above-all attitude, cultivated by a former McKinsey consultant; the significance of hiring a pitcher recently suspended for domestic abuse; the career-ending effects of the Astros’ transgression on opposing players; and the ethically fraught choices necessary to participate in sign-stealing. Ultimately, it links the Astros’ choices to the sporting world’s obsession with analytics. What emerges is a sobering tale about the impact of new technology on a game whose romanticized image feels increasingly incongruous with its reality in the era of big data and video.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBaseball signs and signalszUnited States. 0aBaseballxCorrupt practiceszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSportsxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh  aAltuve, Cora, Beltrán, Hinch, World Series, Baseball, MLB, Osuna, Sports Ethics, Overconformity, Asterisk, McKinsey, Domestic abuse, Sports scandal, Big data, Correa.1 aCrepeau, Richard C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrellich, Evan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGietschier, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGmelch, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinds, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlugman, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeitch, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevin, Allison R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNarcotta-Welp, Eileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNathanson, Mitchell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, Roberta J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRivera, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilverman, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilverman, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStaker, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb